        <h1 id="char">Character</h1>
        <h3 id="char-1">Page 1-6, 13-14, 17-18, 28-30</h3>
        <p>
          The attributes and descriptons remain in place as Harnworld
          requires them (at least for some characters).  In other
          words, without them, a character designed toward a specific
          career would be incomplete in the setting.  They are also
          not transformed in any way.  Generation of values can be
          used as suggested.  <em>Relationship and Loyalty</em> for
          contacts are descriptive only.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sunsigns are treated as direct modifiers, where they have
          a numeric value.
        </p>
        <h3 id="char-2">Page 7-8, 10</h3>
        <p>
          The attributes described are translated (linearly) into the
          range -15 to 15.  <em>Moraliy</em> is dropped.  Generation
          of values can be used as suggested.
        </p>
        <h3 id="char-3">Page 9, 11-12</h3>
        <p>
          Table results from these page are used purely in their
          descriptive sense.  Whether they retroractively have any
          effect on other attributes is a choice that can be made
          during character creation and according to the severity or
          interpretation of the result that you want to portait.
          <em>Piety</em> is turned into a skill (q.v.) for each deity.
          For a single deity the value can be chosen or generated as
          suggested.  All others are 0 initially.
        </p>
        <h4 id="piety">Piety</h4>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN knows that the reigion exist but cannot
            separate it from other convocations.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 5:</b> Lip service payed to the religion and
            ability to separate it from other major faiths.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> The main tenants of the religion are
            known and followed on individual level.  Sects or heresies
            are not considered.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 15:</b> The religion is quoted often and other
            faiths routinely treated underhanded.  Proselytizing is
            rarely attempted.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> At this level the adherent is actively
            seeking to further the tenants of the religion outside of
            his immediate domain.  Distinction between inner-religion
            minutiae are important.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 25:</b> Heresy is abhorred more than other
            religions.  Support for the religion takes precendents
            over other interests almost always.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> The adherent is a prophet for the
            religion and accepts otherwise serious consequences for
            following details of his faith.  May invent rituals and
            the like.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3 id="char-4">Page 15</h3>
        <p>
          The occupations of the table on this page serve as skills
          and the listed "old" skills serve only as descriptive
          values.
        </p>
        <h3 id="char-5">Page 16, 19</h3>
        <p>
          <em>Automatic</em> skills are determined accoridng to the
          appropriate skill section (q.v.) and <em>Occupation</em>
          skills work as transformed for the previous page.  They open
          as 20 for the chosen occupation.  <em>Family</em> skills for
          parents in the same occupation add 2 points, while for a
          different occupation they add 5.  (This is effectively
          <em>Row-5-addition</em> of a 0 skill level.)
          <em>Optional</em> skills are as they exist, but new skills
          may be "invented"; the scope is at GM discretion.  Any
          reasoonable skill can be improved by 5 for each option point
          (OP) through <em>Row-5-addition</em>; this includes OPs
          gained for Veterans.  Militia skills are explained elsewhere
          as are psionics.
        </p>
        <h3 id="char-6">Page 20-22</h3>
        <p>
          Rules on these page are completely dropped currently.
          Generation of values can be used as suggested.
        </p>
        <h3 id="char-6">Page 23-27</h3>
        <p>
          Each clerical occupation is treated as a separate
          occupation, with the "old" skills being used in a
          descriptive sense.  The same is true for the Shek-Pvar.
          <em>Chantry Applications</em> are dropped.  Treat Sunsigns
          as direct modifiers from the <em>Convocational
          Sunsign Modifiers</em> for magic invocations.  Magic does
          not work along spell lines (q.v.).  Each military occupation
          is treated as a separate occupation as well.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="container">
        <h1 id="skills">Skills</h1>
        <p>
          Available skills are according to the occupations listed
          above, determined by Harnworld professions.  More skills may
          be created according to players' or GM's wishes.  A
          selection of often used skills that do not easily relate to
          occupations is given below
        </p>
        <p>
          Situations which require rolls are announced by the GM with
          a general description of what needs to be resolved.  Players
          will then argue, which skills could be applicable and the GM
          will give a corresponding percentage of how much they apply.
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, an assessemnt of the correct political relation
          between to rival noble families may be Herald/75% and
          Knight/50%, and Mercantyler/25%.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now roll for all applicable skills you have a value in.
          (Remember that a base 0 always applies.)  In the example
          above, the mercantyler has a 1 in 4 chance of using his
          mercantyler skill, say 12, and a 3 in 4 chance of using his
          knight skill 0.  All skills which were succeessfully rolled
          for are added up through row 3 from the main rules additions
          table (repeated here).  The end result is the skill to roll
          against.
        </p>
