        <h3 id="skill-1">Page 1-2, 5</h3>
        <p>
          These pages are ignored.
        </p>
        <h3 id="skill-2">Page 3-4</h3>
        <p>
          Sunsigns affect certain applications of skills.  Since the "old"
          skills still remain in their descriptive sense, a player
          should announce, when he feels like his sunsign would apply
          to a situation.  Sunsigns are direct modifiers.
        </p>
        <p>
          Certain applications of skills are provided with result
          tables to allow comparisons.
        </p>
        <h3 id="skill-3">Page 6</h3>
        <p>
          All penalties described are available and will be used
          where they makes sense individually. They are applied to
          a skill level or attribute level as direct modifier an
          they are neither restricted to certain tests nor do they
          automatically apply to others.  The <em>encumbrance
          penalty</em> is calculated from the derived attribute of
          the same name, see the tables.
        </p>
        <p>
          Fatigue is recovered at a rate of 1 level per minute.
        </p>
        <h3 id="skill-3">Page 7</h3>
        <p>
          Learning is modelled by an active roll with level 0 against
          a passive level of the current skill. Note that rolling 10
          non-stop events can be shortened into rolling a 1 with a d10.
          Learning is applicable to attributes but the active roll is
          level -15.
        </p>
        <p>
          Such rolls may be made once a month in which the skill was
          used reasonably often. Usually only three such rolls apply.
          A teacher can also be combined with his own skill reduced by
          10 through <em>Row-5-addition</em>. This assumes that the
          teacher is available almost always during that time.
        </p>
        <p>
          Example: Suppose your skill is at 5 and your teacher has a
          skill of 12. According to the rules, we should first take the
          highest of the two parameters to be combined into a single
          skill roll, that is 0 and 2 (12 - 10).  Remember your active
          level is 0 in this situation.  Taking the difference of, we
          have a column index of 2 into the combination table and we
          read in the fifth row a 5, which will be added to 2 (the
          higher of the two numbers) to yield a 7. That is the active
          skill level to roll against your current skill level (5) to 
          improve.  We are pitting a 7 against a 5 with roughly a 70%
          chance of success and upon success the skill level is increased
          to 6.
        </p>
        <p>
          If a more pragmatic approach is desired, use the following 
          "reversed" table for finding the addition.
        </p>
